# Exception Handling Patterns

## 📌 OVERVIEW

Exception handling ensures consistent, secure, and predictable API error responses.

---

## 🎯 GOAL

* Handle all exceptions centrally
* Return consistent error responses
* Avoid exposing internal details

---

## ⚙️ GLOBAL EXCEPTION HANDLING (MANDATORY)

### DO

* Use `@RestControllerAdvice`
* Handle all exceptions in one place

### EXAMPLE

```java
@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleGeneric(Exception ex, HttpServletRequest request) {
        ErrorResponse error = new ErrorResponse(
            500,
            "Internal server error",
            request.getRequestURI()
        );
        return ResponseEntity.status(500).body(error);
    }
}
```

---

## 📦 ERROR RESPONSE FORMAT

### DO

* Use consistent structure

### STANDARD RESPONSE

```java
public class ErrorResponse {

    private int statusCode;
    private String message;
    private String path;
    private String timestamp;

    public ErrorResponse(int statusCode, String message, String path) {
        this.statusCode = statusCode;
        this.message = message;
        this.path = path;
        this.timestamp = java.time.Instant.now().toString();
    }
}
```

---

## ❗ COMMON EXCEPTIONS

### DO

* Use standard exceptions:

```java
throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid input");
throw new RuntimeException("Something went wrong");
```

### PREFERRED (CUSTOM)

```java
throw new ResourceNotFoundException("Task not found");
throw new BadRequestException("Invalid request");
```

---

## 🧱 CUSTOM EXCEPTIONS

### DO

* Create custom exceptions for business logic

### EXAMPLE

```java
public class ResourceNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public ResourceNotFoundException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
```

---

## 🔄 HANDLE SPECIFIC EXCEPTIONS

### DO

* Handle known exceptions explicitly

### EXAMPLE

```java
@ExceptionHandler(ResourceNotFoundException.class)
public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleNotFound(
        ResourceNotFoundException ex,
        HttpServletRequest request) {

    ErrorResponse error = new ErrorResponse(
        404,
        ex.getMessage(),
        request.getRequestURI()
    );

    return ResponseEntity.status(404).body(error);
}
```

---

## 🧾 VALIDATION EXCEPTIONS

### DO

* Handle validation errors from `@Valid`

### EXAMPLE

```java
@ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
public ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> handleValidation(
        MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {

    Map<String, String> errors = new HashMap<>();

    ex.getBindingResult().getFieldErrors().forEach(error ->
        errors.put(error.getField(), error.getDefaultMessage())
    );

    return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(errors);
}
```

---

## 🚫 DO NOT RULES

* Do not handle exceptions inside controllers
* Do not return stack traces
* Do not expose internal error messages
* Do not use generic error responses without structure

---

## ⚙️ SERVICE LAYER RULES

### DO

* Throw exceptions from service layer
* Handle business logic errors here

### DO NOT

* Do not catch exceptions unless necessary

---

## 🧪 TDD RULES FOR EXCEPTIONS

### DO

* Write tests for failure cases
* Verify correct exception is thrown

### EXAMPLE

```java
@Test
void shouldThrowNotFoundWhenTaskMissing() {
    when(repository.findById(1L)).thenReturn(Optional.empty());

    assertThrows(ResourceNotFoundException.class,
        () -> service.getTask(1L));
}
```

---

## 📊 STATUS CODE MAPPING

### DO

* Map exceptions to HTTP status:

* 400 → BadRequestException

* 404 → ResourceNotFoundException

* 409 → ConflictException

* 500 → Generic Exception

---

## 🧠 AI ENFORCEMENT RULES

* MUST use global exception handler
* MUST return structured error response
* MUST NOT expose stack traces
* MUST throw exceptions from service layer
* MUST handle validation errors

